1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,400
In this video, we'll go through some of

2
00:00:02,400 --> 00:00:06,090
the most common and useful plots you can create with pandas.

3
00:00:06,090 --> 00:00:08,670
Note that the plot methods on a series or

4
00:00:08,670 --> 00:00:12,480
DataFrame are just simple wrappers around matplotlib functions.

5
00:00:12,480 --> 00:00:15,675
This is why you might see them used interchangeably,

6
00:00:15,675 --> 00:00:18,120
pandas is nice for quick insights,

7
00:00:18,120 --> 00:00:20,790
but you'll need to use matplotlib to really dive into

8
00:00:20,790 --> 00:00:23,775
details and customize your visualizations.

9
00:00:23,775 --> 00:00:25,890
We'll get into this more later on.

10
00:00:25,890 --> 00:00:29,550
Let's first use census income data to practice plotting histograms,

11
00:00:29,550 --> 00:00:32,175
bar charts, and pie charts in pandas.

12
00:00:32,175 --> 00:00:35,670
A really useful line to include when visualizing in

13
00:00:35,670 --> 00:00:39,015
Jupyter Notebooks is the matplotlib in-line statement.

14
00:00:39,015 --> 00:00:42,340
This lets you view your plots in the notebook.

15
00:00:46,330 --> 00:00:49,100
A quick way to view histograms for

16
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:52,850
all numerical columns in a DataFrame is the hist function,

17
00:00:52,850 --> 00:00:55,945
which we could call directly on the pandas DataFrame.

18
00:00:55,945 --> 00:00:57,710
That was way too crowded.

19
00:00:57,710 --> 00:01:00,150
Let's make our figure size bigger.

20
00:01:00,910 --> 00:01:06,180
Also, we can use a semicolon to suppress this unwanted output.

21
00:01:09,470 --> 00:01:13,880
The hist function can also be called on a pandas series object.

22
00:01:13,880 --> 00:01:18,380
We can plot a histogram for one specific column like this.

23
00:01:19,700 --> 00:01:22,480
Or instead of using hist,

24
00:01:22,480 --> 00:01:28,080
the more general plot function and specify the type of plot in a parameter.

25
00:01:29,780 --> 00:01:34,055
Next, let's plot a bar chart for the education column.

26
00:01:34,055 --> 00:01:38,940
For this, we need counts for each distinct value or bar.

27
00:01:39,560 --> 00:01:45,635
This value counts function aggregates counts for each unique value in a column.

28
00:01:45,635 --> 00:01:50,125
We can call the plot function on this result to create a bar chart.

29
00:01:50,125 --> 00:01:54,185
Similarly, we also need value counts to plot pie charts.

30
00:01:54,185 --> 00:01:57,110
Let's create a pie chart for the workclass column.

31
00:01:57,110 --> 00:01:59,240
Awesome. Let's switch to

32
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:03,990
our cancer dataset to practice plotting scatter plots and box plots.

33
00:02:04,100 --> 00:02:08,240
This next function is really cool for getting quick insight

34
00:02:08,240 --> 00:02:12,035
into the relationships among numerical variables with scatter plots.

35
00:02:12,035 --> 00:02:16,020
It also displays a histogram for each variable.

36
00:02:16,360 --> 00:02:20,900
We can create a single scatter plot using this standard plot function,

37
00:02:20,900 --> 00:02:25,420
with parameters to specify the columns to be used for the x and y-axis.

38
00:02:25,420 --> 00:02:30,270
Finally, the plot function can also be used to create a boxplot.

